ifferent life stages, and look forward to hopes for future intimacies. In the navigation of romance and new relationships we see the sensory, sensual and affective nature of heteronormativity, and gendered practices that are informed by memories of the past, the imagination of previous generations and class-based desires. Challenging conventional notions of the baby boomers, this book illuminates the intersections of age, class, and white normativity, making important contributions to our understanding of ageing and generation, intimacy and gender.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aBaby boomers.  aclass.  adance.  aethnography.  afemininity.  aheterosexuality.  aintersectionality.  amidlife.  aoral history.  arace.1 aMilton, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152616807840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526168078423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526168078/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles